SIMPLE: find
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Find
<hw>Find</hw> <pr>(f⟦imac⟧nd)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Found</conjf> <pr>(found)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Finding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>findan</ets>;
akin to D. <ets>vinden</ets>, OS. & OHG. <ets>findan</ets>, G.
<ets>finden</ets>, Dan. <ets>finde</ets>, icel. & Sw. <ets>finna</ets>,
Goth. <ets>fin⟦thorn⟧an</ets>; and perh. to L. <ets>petere</ets> to
seek, Gr. <grk>pi`ptein</grk> to fall, Skr. <ets>pat</ets> to fall, fly,
E. <ets>petition</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To meet with, or light
upon, accidentally; to gain the first sight or knowledge of, as of
something new, or unknown; hence, to fall in with, as a
person.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Searching the window for a flint, I <qex>found</qex>⟦br⟧
This paper, thus sealed up.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In woods and forests thou art <qex>found</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To learn by experience or trial; to perceive; to
experience; to discover by the intellect or the feelings; to detect; to
feel.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧I <xex>find</xex> you passing gentle.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The torrid zone is now <qex>found</qex> habitable.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To come upon by seeking; <as>as, to <ex>find</ex>
something lost</as>.</def> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To discover by sounding;
<as>as, to <ex>find</ex> bottom</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To
discover by study or experiment direct to an object or end; <as>as,
water is <ex>found</ex> to be a compound substance</as>.</def>
<sd>(c)</sd> <def>To gain, as the object of desire or effort; <as>as, to
<ex>find</ex> leisure; to <ex>find</ex> means</as>.</def> <sd>(d)</sd>
<def>To attain to; to arrive at; to acquire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seek, and ye shall <qex>find</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. vii.
7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every mountain now hath <qex>found</qex> a tongue.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To provide for; to supply; to furnish; <as>as, to
<ex>find</ex> food for workemen; he <ex>finds</ex> his nephew in
money.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wages ⟦pound⟧14 and all <qex>found</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>London
Times.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing a day and <qex>find</qex> yourself.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj> <-- obsolete?? -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To arrive at, as a conclusion; to determine as true;
to establish; <as>as, to <ex>find</ex> a verdict; to <ex>find</ex> a
true bill (of indictment) against an accused person.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>find</qex> his title with some shows of truth.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To find out</b></col>, <cd>to detect (a thief); to
discover (a secret) -- to solve or unriddle (a parable or enigma); to
understand.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Canst thou by searching <xex>find out</xex>
God?⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Job. xi. 7.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧We do hope <xex>to find
out</xex> all your tricks.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au> -- <col><b>To find
fault with</b></col>, <cd>to blame; to censure.</cd> -- <col><b>To find
one's self</b></col>, <cd>to be; to fare; -- often used in speaking of
health; <as>as, how do you <ex>find yourself</ex> this
morning?</as></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Find</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Find
<hw>Find</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To
determine an issue of fact, and to declare such a determination to a
court; <as>as, the jury <ex>find</ex> for the plaintiff</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Find</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Find
<hw>Find</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Anything found; a discovery of
anything valuable; especially, a deposit, discovered by
arch⟦ae⟧ologists, of objects of prehistoric or unknown origin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Findable</ent>⟦br⟧
